            <fr:title text="The positive elements of a pointed dcpo">The positive elements of a pointed dcpo</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>An element <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u]]></fr:tex> of a <fr:link href="jms-001S.xml" title="Pointed dcpo" addr="jms-001S" type="local">pointed</fr:link> dpco <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> is called <fr:em>positive</fr:em> when for any semidirected subset <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I\subseteq  A]]></fr:tex>, if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u\sqsubseteq  \bigsqcup {I}]]></fr:tex> then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I]]></fr:tex> is inhabited. We will write <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {pos}\,{u}]]></fr:tex> to mean that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u]]></fr:tex> is a positive element.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>(This is adapted from <fr:link href="johnstone-1984.xml" title="Open locales and exponentiation" addr="johnstone-1984" type="local">Johnstone</fr:link>’s definition of positive elements of frames to the case of dcpos by <fr:link href="dejong-2023-thesis.xml" title="Domain theory in constructive and predicative univalent foundations" addr="dejong-2023-thesis" type="local">Tom de Jong</fr:link>.)</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
